The paper deals with the problem of detecting anomalous random variables from a collection of independent random variables. The approach involves conducting hypothesis tests based on mixed observations of the random variables, which is related to compressed sensing. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely sub-category as it deals with compressed sensing and signal processing. The paper also involves the use of algorithms for detecting jointly sparse signals and their support from multiple measurement vectors, which falls under cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also involves experiments on synthetic data, which falls under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). The paper also involves the study of the trade-off between the number of mixed observations per sample and the number of samples required to detect anomalies, which falls under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.SP (Signal Processing).
